WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.000
This is joint work with Michael Sumner, who is regrettably not here, and Etienne Racine,

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:19.680
who is here, sitting in the forefront, and I'm pretty confident, I think I can promise

00:00:19.680 --> 00:00:27.920
you that I will be the only talk in this session without moving images.

00:00:27.920 --> 00:00:34.360
So I talked last year about simple features, and I couldn't find a better summary than

00:00:34.360 --> 00:00:43.419
this lovely graph, this lovely illustration that Alison Horst posted on Twitter recently.

00:00:43.419 --> 00:00:48.119
Simple features basically makes handling feature data, so that's points, lines, and polygon

00:00:48.119 --> 00:00:55.680
data easier, spatial data easier in R, because it kind of glues stuff as an additional column

00:00:55.680 --> 00:01:00.439
in your table, in your data frame or table, and it keeps them there, and then you can

00:01:00.439 --> 00:01:03.560
do all your regular manipulations with that.

00:01:03.560 --> 00:01:10.400
In addition, you can do all kind of spatial operations, like spatial joins and operating

00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:13.080
on the geometries.

00:01:13.080 --> 00:01:17.720
So that was sort of caught up very well, that is the good news.

00:01:17.720 --> 00:01:23.279
So there's a strong uptake of simple feature package by both users and developers, and

00:01:23.279 --> 00:01:27.720
we improved by that the interoperability with spatial databases, GeoJSON, and also

00:01:27.720 --> 00:01:33.839
off-corner reference system handling in R. Also spatial indexes are computed in fly,

00:01:33.839 --> 00:01:41.500
for instance, by ST intersect, and we have now also plot support in ggplot2 that takes

00:01:41.500 --> 00:01:45.680
care of reprojecting incompatible layers.

00:01:45.680 --> 00:01:53.839
There is an additional thing that we added to the simple feature package, and that is

00:01:53.839 --> 00:01:59.680
the issue, like, it is very easy to find out whether a point lies inside a polygon or not.

00:01:59.680 --> 00:02:01.199
That's a simple geometry problem.

00:02:01.199 --> 00:02:07.680
But then if you work with properties, like you saw here in this graph that we work with

00:02:07.680 --> 00:02:12.660
geometries and properties of these geometries, it's not so easy to assess when you query

00:02:12.660 --> 00:02:16.619
a point in a polygon to assess what a value would be.

00:02:16.619 --> 00:02:20.619
So if you have on the left-hand side, for instance, a land use map, you could reasonably

00:02:20.619 --> 00:02:25.660
say that at a particular point in that polygon, the land use will be forest, but if you have

00:02:25.660 --> 00:02:30.539
a population density map, which is also a polygon with a value, you cannot say that

00:02:30.539 --> 00:02:35.059
because the population density is an aggregate property over the entire polygon.

00:02:35.059 --> 00:02:40.179
So we made categories for that, and that information is propagated, and if you don't know or if

00:02:40.179 --> 00:02:45.699
you are on the right-hand side of the figure, you get warnings when you query these points

00:02:45.699 --> 00:02:51.500
that you basically make assumptions that are not sort of supported by the data.

00:02:51.500 --> 00:02:52.899
So this is all very nice.

00:02:52.899 --> 00:02:58.660
It starts getting sort of challenging, more challenging when you have time-dependent data.

00:02:58.660 --> 00:03:04.100
So here we have the classical North Carolina sudden infant death data set where we have

00:03:04.100 --> 00:03:08.460
two rounds of measurements in 74 and 79.

00:03:08.460 --> 00:03:17.139
This is one of the first published spatial statistics data sets.

00:03:17.139 --> 00:03:21.820
And we can sort of plot them, and then basically we have them as two columns in the data set,

00:03:21.820 --> 00:03:26.539
and we need to use Garter here to stack them into a single column, and then we have to

00:03:26.539 --> 00:03:29.619
replicate all the geometries, and we can do that.

00:03:29.619 --> 00:03:34.779
But then what happens if you have like 50 instances of time, or when you have 500 or

00:03:34.779 --> 00:03:38.940
1,000, you would have like 5,000 columns, and you are going to stack all of them and

00:03:38.940 --> 00:03:39.940
so on.

00:03:39.940 --> 00:03:42.740
It's getting very messy.

00:03:42.740 --> 00:03:46.899
And also keeping time in columns is not a good idea at all, because where do you put

00:03:46.899 --> 00:03:47.899
the timestamp?

00:03:47.899 --> 00:03:50.860
So you would have to put it in the column name.

00:03:50.860 --> 00:03:53.059
So time is an issue there.

00:03:53.059 --> 00:03:54.059
We have time-dependent data.

00:03:54.059 --> 00:03:55.059
Where do we put it?

00:03:55.059 --> 00:03:57.699
Over multiple columns, or do we recycle features?

00:03:57.699 --> 00:04:03.820
If we put it in a long, in a tidy table, that is all sort of not ideal.

00:04:03.860 --> 00:04:06.139
Easy plotting is something of an issue.

00:04:06.139 --> 00:04:11.059
There is also a sort of recurring question of the support for raster data and the solid

00:04:11.059 --> 00:04:13.259
vector and raster integration.

00:04:13.259 --> 00:04:18.220
This is something you can emulate by sort of having points on the raster or little square

00:04:18.220 --> 00:04:22.500
polygons, but it is not going to bring you far in the sense of scaling.

00:04:22.500 --> 00:04:26.100
Why raster data for those not involved in the raster world?

00:04:26.100 --> 00:04:32.100
Well, variables that vary continuously over space or over time are typically represented

00:04:32.100 --> 00:04:34.100
more naturally by regular sampling.

00:04:34.100 --> 00:04:39.660
So think images do that still, images or video, but also Earth observation data.

00:04:39.660 --> 00:04:48.420
So satellite data, we have now visible satellites that give information about land, about ocean,

00:04:48.420 --> 00:04:50.559
about temperature, radar satellites.

00:04:50.559 --> 00:04:53.260
We have satellites that measure atmospheric composition.

00:04:53.260 --> 00:04:56.299
And these all come down freely now.

00:04:56.299 --> 00:04:59.019
Europe is here clearly on the ball at the moment.

00:04:59.019 --> 00:05:02.820
In the Copernicus program where they have like a little bit less than 10 satellites

00:05:02.820 --> 00:05:06.700
now running, it comes down to 150 terabytes per day.

00:05:06.700 --> 00:05:14.179
So that's quite a bandwidth, sort of the data sets that you can have access to.

00:05:14.179 --> 00:05:18.540
Also climate data, climate model data is also free and large.

00:05:18.540 --> 00:05:24.019
The climate, the coupled model intercomparison program will generate sort of over a couple

00:05:24.019 --> 00:05:28.299
of years, around six, will generate 15 to 30 petabytes.

00:05:28.299 --> 00:05:31.059
That's a data center, I imagine.

00:05:31.059 --> 00:05:35.179
And there are numerous other sources of raster data that are interesting.

00:05:35.179 --> 00:05:40.380
And that is also what really motivates me, that there is so incredibly much free information

00:05:40.380 --> 00:05:47.260
that is collected or generated that you could get access to and use if you could use it,

00:05:47.260 --> 00:05:48.260
right?

00:05:48.260 --> 00:05:50.480
But it is so hard to do it quite often.

00:05:50.480 --> 00:05:55.980
So here's an example of an image that comes from the Sentinel-5P that where six months

00:05:55.980 --> 00:05:58.420
of data were sort of thrown together.

00:05:58.420 --> 00:06:02.859
And this looks like what you typically see from models, but this is actually measurement.

00:06:02.859 --> 00:06:06.859
This is measured atmospheric composition.

00:06:06.859 --> 00:06:11.559
So this is six months of imagery compiled together, and you see sort of for those living

00:06:11.559 --> 00:06:13.459
in Europe, you see a fairly familiar pattern.

00:06:13.459 --> 00:06:19.480
But what you, for instance, also see is the ship lines flowing here.

00:06:19.480 --> 00:06:25.140
So you see even the NO2 emitted by sea traffic.

00:06:25.299 --> 00:06:28.299
And it is quite revolutionary that you get this from pure measurements.

00:06:28.299 --> 00:06:32.059
There's, of course, a lot of heavy processing going on there.

00:06:32.059 --> 00:06:37.059
The thing to sort of the way out to handle time properly and to deal with raster data

00:06:37.059 --> 00:06:41.579
and to deal with more complicated data, in my eyes, was that of data cubes.

00:06:41.579 --> 00:06:47.339
Data cubes, the idea of data cubes go back to OLAP cues, which is sort of there's a paper

00:06:47.339 --> 00:06:52.739
from Jim Gray on this, mentioned on Wikipedia from 1996, sort of where values basically

00:06:52.739 --> 00:06:56.820
are given for each combination of dimensions for dimension values.

00:06:56.820 --> 00:06:59.459
So we can have sales by product, store, and week.

00:06:59.459 --> 00:07:03.820
So for every combination of product, of store, and week, we get a sales figure.

00:07:03.820 --> 00:07:08.239
We can have population by gender, age, class, region, and census around.

00:07:08.239 --> 00:07:11.339
We can have temperature by XYZ and time.

00:07:11.339 --> 00:07:15.660
Four-dimensional data cube, we can have screen pixels here, like which are two-dimensional

00:07:15.660 --> 00:07:18.899
or which vary, and then it's three-dimensional, like video.

00:07:18.899 --> 00:07:23.540
We can have also forecasts, so like weather forecast, by time of forecast, and time to

00:07:23.540 --> 00:07:24.540
forecast.

00:07:24.540 --> 00:07:27.519
So we have two dimensions of time covering time.

00:07:27.519 --> 00:07:32.980
And that sort of varies down by variable, by XY and altitude.

00:07:32.980 --> 00:07:39.059
Why not handle them entirely as tidy, as long tables, as Iaro would suggest in that symbol?

00:07:39.059 --> 00:07:41.980
Well, there is storage to speed and indexes, right?

00:07:41.980 --> 00:07:52.500
I sort of welcome anyone to put a video stream into a sort of XY time red, green, blue dataset.

00:07:52.500 --> 00:07:54.000
You don't do that.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:08:03.619
So you could do it, but it's not going to scale up really much, only for smaller subsets.

00:08:03.619 --> 00:08:07.220
So what we do is basically working with arrays, right?

00:08:07.220 --> 00:08:12.420
And arrays are, the array has a long history of support in a base and also in dplyr.

00:08:12.420 --> 00:08:17.500
So base array is a very strong structure that has dim names, and dim names are pretty limited

00:08:17.500 --> 00:08:18.500
because they're characters.

00:08:18.500 --> 00:08:22.899
So if you want to put time in dim names, then you have to encode it as character and it's

00:08:22.899 --> 00:08:23.899
messy.

00:08:23.899 --> 00:08:28.059
But the good thing is that you can use apply, so that means you can sort of cut out, you

00:08:28.059 --> 00:08:31.100
can aggregate of particular sets of dimensions.

00:08:31.100 --> 00:08:35.659
You can do subsetting for slicing, cropping, and slicing and dicing.

00:08:35.659 --> 00:08:38.500
There's a bind support, arrays are atomic.

00:08:38.500 --> 00:08:44.340
Then there's the table cube in dplyr, which is sort of a structure that hasn't received

00:08:44.340 --> 00:08:52.140
very much love or exposure, but it's relatively a cool idea to list of arrays, and it mimics

00:08:52.140 --> 00:08:56.059
by that basically heterogeneous array records.

00:08:56.059 --> 00:08:59.700
And it has an additional list effector with dimension values that's much more flexible

00:08:59.700 --> 00:09:04.340
than dim names that can also have like date, date structures and so on, and it has filter

00:09:04.340 --> 00:09:06.059
methods and group by stuff.

00:09:06.059 --> 00:09:11.340
But it cannot, for instance, deal with simple features as dimensions, which you would do.

00:09:11.340 --> 00:09:15.659
So and it doesn't also doesn't have support for regular dimension, meaning if I want to

00:09:15.659 --> 00:09:20.940
map sort of my space linearly to a dimension index.

00:09:20.940 --> 00:09:24.619
So what we do in the stars package, in the stars project, is to implement raster and

00:09:24.619 --> 00:09:29.820
factor data cubes, and those are MD cubes where one or more of the dimensions relate

00:09:29.820 --> 00:09:33.940
to space and typically also to time.

00:09:33.940 --> 00:09:38.059
The raster data cubes typically have x and y, take spatial dimensions, effector cubes,

00:09:38.059 --> 00:09:44.539
have a single dimension that sort of lists the points, lines of polygons that the index

00:09:44.539 --> 00:09:45.859
refers to.

00:09:45.859 --> 00:09:52.260
And then we have, we basically have a list of arrays and sets of dimensions, have regular

00:09:52.260 --> 00:09:57.419
dimensions, dimensions as values, and take care of measurement units and code and reference

00:09:57.419 --> 00:10:03.739
systems, do the I.O. with GDAL, which we already did with SF, also do a lot of work with net

00:10:03.739 --> 00:10:08.020
CDF, which Michael Sumner is very instrumental in that side.

00:10:08.020 --> 00:10:12.539
And we support out-of-core, and we will support cloud processing, and we'll say a little bit

00:10:12.539 --> 00:10:13.859
about how that works.

00:10:13.859 --> 00:10:15.539
So you think that raster types are easy.

00:10:15.539 --> 00:10:16.539
Well, they're not.

00:10:16.539 --> 00:10:17.859
So there are all these kind of varieties.

00:10:17.859 --> 00:10:20.059
This is the nightmare for the developer.

00:10:20.059 --> 00:10:24.979
The first three sort of have linearly mapped array index to x and y.

00:10:24.979 --> 00:10:26.659
The last two do not do that.

00:10:26.659 --> 00:10:31.299
This is like a graticule, but basically if you have a regular raster on the earth and

00:10:31.299 --> 00:10:35.659
you then project it, then it becomes automatically curvilinear unless you do resampling to a

00:10:35.659 --> 00:10:40.099
new regular raster, which is what GDAL calls warping.

00:10:40.099 --> 00:10:45.299
So here's an image similar to what I showed last year of what STARS does.

00:10:45.299 --> 00:10:51.020
So we read here a little geotiff, but here we use ggplot and we use a geomSTARS, which

00:10:51.020 --> 00:10:55.700
is very primitive, which is a 10-line function that essentially decides should I call geomRaster

00:10:55.700 --> 00:11:01.580
or should I call geomTile, depending on what I have, or geomRect, it was geomRaster or

00:11:01.580 --> 00:11:02.580
geomRect.

00:11:02.580 --> 00:11:09.219
In any case, a lot of other things you still need to do, like coordinate equal and so on.

00:11:09.219 --> 00:11:12.219
And this basically plots what is there, plots the data.

00:11:12.219 --> 00:11:18.179
And that is kind of okay, but it sort of makes it into a long data frame and then plots all

00:11:18.179 --> 00:11:19.419
of the pixels.

00:11:19.419 --> 00:11:24.659
And that is okay up to the moment that your data are sort of, you know, this size that

00:11:24.659 --> 00:11:25.659
you have.

00:11:25.659 --> 00:11:31.539
Like a typical Sentinel-2 image has 10,000 by 10,000 pixels, which means it's a 100-kilometer

00:11:31.539 --> 00:11:35.299
by 100-kilometer area with 10-meter grid cells.

00:11:35.299 --> 00:11:39.340
So this is the state of the art in visible remote sensing, free data.

00:11:39.340 --> 00:11:46.539
Of course, intelligence data, spy satellites have a much higher resolution, but they're

00:11:46.539 --> 00:11:47.539
not open.

00:11:47.659 --> 00:11:50.340
So when you plot this thing, you think, hey, what's happening here?

00:11:50.340 --> 00:11:55.179
The thing is basically read here by saying proxy is true, and what then happens is that

00:11:55.179 --> 00:11:59.059
none of the data is read, that only the metadata is read, meaning that only the dimensions

00:11:59.059 --> 00:12:02.900
are being read, but none of the image pixels are being touched.

00:12:02.900 --> 00:12:06.659
And when I plot this data, and that's why I didn't do it with ggplot and sort of convert

00:12:06.659 --> 00:12:12.700
it into a markdown, because that would sort of take every time 10 minutes before my markdown

00:12:12.700 --> 00:12:15.260
compiled into slides, and you can't work like that.

00:12:15.260 --> 00:12:20.260
So this plot method here looks at, hey, what is my plot sort of area, how many pixels do

00:12:20.260 --> 00:12:21.260
I have there?

00:12:21.260 --> 00:12:23.820
Oh, it's much less than 10,000 by 10,000.

00:12:23.820 --> 00:12:25.520
It's only 800 by 800.

00:12:25.520 --> 00:12:26.780
So let's downsample.

00:12:26.780 --> 00:12:34.140
Let's only read as many pixels as I maximally can view, and then sort of render them and

00:12:34.140 --> 00:12:38.580
throw them to the plot device, and that is sort of in a matter of seconds done compared

00:12:38.580 --> 00:12:40.859
to sort of 5 or 10 minutes.

00:12:40.859 --> 00:12:43.340
And you can continue on this idea.

00:12:43.340 --> 00:12:49.419
So we have an stapply here that is applied to this object, which is still not read, and

00:12:49.419 --> 00:12:53.940
it says to the dimensions x and y, apply this function, which is NDVI, which computes a

00:12:53.940 --> 00:12:58.599
vegetation index by combining two bands, which is this little function.

00:12:58.599 --> 00:13:03.500
So it applies this to every pixel, because I have four bands here.

00:13:03.500 --> 00:13:08.380
It applies it to every pixel, and you think, oh, this is going to take time, because it's

00:13:08.380 --> 00:13:12.580
going to do this for this 10,000 cells, but no, it does nothing, as you see here.

00:13:12.580 --> 00:13:18.460
And only when I plot this thing, then it does something, but then it sort of changes execution

00:13:18.460 --> 00:13:19.460
order.

00:13:19.460 --> 00:13:20.460
It says, oh, I have to plot something.

00:13:20.460 --> 00:13:28.059
That means I can downsample, and it downsamples, and then it reads only the downsampled data,

00:13:28.059 --> 00:13:29.940
computes the NDVI for those, and plots the thing.

00:13:29.940 --> 00:13:36.020
So this is sort of a query optimization, you could say, by this.

00:13:36.020 --> 00:13:39.940
Cloud proxies, something that we have in mind is where the data are basically not in

00:13:39.940 --> 00:13:42.260
your local machine, but in the cloud.

00:13:42.260 --> 00:13:48.380
And the next idea is that of a data cube view, where you basically have dimension settings

00:13:48.380 --> 00:13:52.659
that you don't read from an image, but that you set independently, and we basically query

00:13:52.659 --> 00:13:55.340
the imagery on this setting.

00:13:55.340 --> 00:13:58.979
So you could have, then, for instance, a collection of images that are in different projections,

00:13:58.979 --> 00:14:04.659
like you typically have with Sentinel, with satellite, or also Landsat data that they

00:14:04.659 --> 00:14:09.299
are in over different UDM zones, and sort of handles that, an idea that is pioneered

00:14:09.299 --> 00:14:12.900
and inspired by Google Earth Engine, a very strong platform.

00:14:12.900 --> 00:14:17.580
So a lot of data are, of course, non-cube data, right?

00:14:17.580 --> 00:14:19.460
So we have spatial temporal events.

00:14:19.460 --> 00:14:20.580
We have spatial networks.

00:14:20.580 --> 00:14:21.960
We have movement data.

00:14:21.960 --> 00:14:27.700
And there is a nice sort of data set that is also in the dplyr, available as a subset

00:14:27.700 --> 00:14:33.359
of this in the dplyr package called Storms, from this hurricane data set, which was luckily

00:14:33.359 --> 00:14:35.679
still in the air.

00:14:35.679 --> 00:14:39.280
It's also not updated regularly, I think once per year or something like that.

00:14:39.280 --> 00:14:45.520
This here you see is the color, the year of the hurricane, and the path it took without

00:14:45.520 --> 00:14:49.760
reference, only the latitudes and longitudes.

00:14:49.760 --> 00:14:51.320
And this is difficult to interpret, right?

00:14:51.320 --> 00:14:54.640
So this is a time series, and the question is, like, is there anything changing over

00:14:54.640 --> 00:14:55.640
time?

00:14:55.640 --> 00:14:59.000
But they are all kind of, you know, it's a hairy ball.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:00.159
So what to do with it?

00:15:00.159 --> 00:15:04.640
So you can cut it up, and you can say, oh, this is nice, ggplot, and so on.

00:15:04.640 --> 00:15:07.679
But it's still a lot of hairy balls, and you can't really tell.

00:15:07.679 --> 00:15:09.979
There's a lot of overlap.

00:15:09.979 --> 00:15:13.719
So you can't really say, is anything increasing or decreasing?

00:15:13.719 --> 00:15:17.039
Because all the overlap means you don't know how much there is.

00:15:17.039 --> 00:15:21.320
So what you would do is really sort of make little boxes, and then count in these little

00:15:21.320 --> 00:15:22.320
boxes.

00:15:22.320 --> 00:15:23.960
And that's exactly what I did here.

00:15:23.960 --> 00:15:25.679
So I made little boxes.

00:15:25.679 --> 00:15:28.760
So I made a raster, basically, in two dimensions.

00:15:28.760 --> 00:15:33.679
And then for each of the raster cells, I intersected all of the lines and counted sort

00:15:33.679 --> 00:15:37.880
of when there was sort of a part of the hurricane going through the raster cell.

00:15:37.880 --> 00:15:40.440
I counted, and I counted the number of raster cells.

00:15:40.440 --> 00:15:44.039
And now, if you're really smart, then you think, hey, but this is running from 10 degrees

00:15:44.039 --> 00:15:45.039
to 80 degrees.

00:15:45.039 --> 00:15:50.239
So what's happening here is, of course, that raster cells, if you would distribute them

00:15:50.239 --> 00:15:55.880
regularly over x and y, you get sort of boxes on the earth that are of completely different

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:57.000
size.

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:00.000
Because all the time, they get narrower when you get close to the pole.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:02.000
So this would not sort of work very well.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:08.520
But what I did is I made the y direction increasing.

00:16:08.520 --> 00:16:14.640
So they're very narrow in the south, and they get sort of taller when you get more north.

00:16:14.640 --> 00:16:19.919
So it's such that we have approximately equal areas for these boxes.

00:16:19.919 --> 00:16:22.640
And that means it's a rectilinear grid.

00:16:22.640 --> 00:16:26.119
And then counts are proportional to densities.

00:16:26.119 --> 00:16:29.479
And you could, of course, that ignores length, and duration, and strength.

00:16:29.479 --> 00:16:33.039
So you can do much more with this data.

00:16:33.039 --> 00:16:37.159
But this is a very sort of simple analysis that I started with.

00:16:37.159 --> 00:16:41.840
So to conclude, spatial data science is an exciting field full with data, maps, challenges,

00:16:41.840 --> 00:16:43.760
and tidyverse extensions.

00:16:43.760 --> 00:16:47.640
With SF, the simple features package, we extend the tables to spatial tables.

00:16:47.640 --> 00:16:51.460
And with the stars package, we extend that to roster and vector data cubes.

00:16:51.460 --> 00:16:55.340
And that includes spatial time series as a special case.

00:16:55.340 --> 00:17:00.940
Stars can do out-of-core roster, is lazy, does some optimizations there, and will eventually

00:17:00.940 --> 00:17:06.180
address also cloud roster processing, which is where everything is going in this world

00:17:06.180 --> 00:17:09.739
in terms of these data sizes to do something useful.

00:17:09.739 --> 00:17:15.060
We can analyze big image collections interactively only when we downsample cleverly.

00:17:15.060 --> 00:17:19.140
And there is more to read about sort of the stuff that we do in the book that I'm writing

00:17:19.140 --> 00:17:24.140
together with Roger Biven called Spatial Data Science, which has a link here.

00:17:24.140 --> 00:17:28.780
So the slides are in a tweet that I sent an hour ago, the link to the slides.

00:17:28.780 --> 00:17:34.260
And also, I want to sort of draw your attention to a spatial birds of feather meeting, which

00:17:34.260 --> 00:17:36.780
takes place tomorrow at breakfast.

00:17:36.780 --> 00:17:37.780
Thank you very much.

00:17:37.780 --> 00:17:38.780
Thank you so much, Edzer.

00:17:38.780 --> 00:17:47.780
And we have time for a couple of questions.

00:17:48.780 --> 00:18:05.780
If you could stand up and raise your hand, that would be helpful.

00:18:06.780 --> 00:18:23.780
So how is SF and stars going to interoperate?

00:18:23.780 --> 00:18:25.780
Could you repeat that?

00:18:25.780 --> 00:18:29.780
So SF is for vector spatial data, and stars is for raster.

00:18:29.780 --> 00:18:34.780
Are they going to interoperate in some sense to align the coordinate system?

00:18:35.780 --> 00:18:43.780
I should have put this full with vector data cubes.

00:18:43.780 --> 00:18:45.780
So this is the confusion.

00:18:45.780 --> 00:18:49.780
The confusion is this, that stars is about raster data.

00:18:49.780 --> 00:18:50.780
Yes?

00:18:50.780 --> 00:18:52.780
But stars is about spatial temporal data cubes.

00:18:52.780 --> 00:18:56.780
And there are two types of data cubes, raster data cubes and vector data cubes.

00:18:56.780 --> 00:19:06.780
So if you have this kind of data geometries with time series, then geometries is one dimension,

00:19:06.780 --> 00:19:08.780
and time is another one.

00:19:08.780 --> 00:19:15.780
And you could have population data per region by age class for different censuses.

00:19:15.780 --> 00:19:21.780
And you have a 3D vector data cube, where space takes only one dimension.

00:19:21.780 --> 00:19:23.780
So it does both.

00:19:23.780 --> 00:19:25.780
And by that, it integrates it automatically.

00:19:25.780 --> 00:19:32.780
So you could do an aggregation over your raster and reduce the x and y dimension into a set of features,

00:19:32.780 --> 00:19:34.780
which could be polygons.

00:19:34.780 --> 00:19:35.780
Thank you.

00:19:35.780 --> 00:19:38.780
Good question.

00:19:38.780 --> 00:19:40.780
No further questions?

00:19:40.780 --> 00:19:42.780
All right.

